<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-572-514  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 572 514.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  August 22 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Japanese to German translation system.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Takahashi, Ken.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Aris Software-Entwicklung GmbH (product development)Fujitsu Ltd. (product development).andO;Topic:     Software PublishersSoftware packagesProduct DevelopmentLanguage TranslationJapanese LanguageGerman LanguageCooperative Agreement.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>JAPANESE TO GERMAN TRANSLATION SYSTEM TOKYO, JAPAN, 1989 AUG 15 (NB) --Fujitsu and West Germany-based software house Aris Software-Entwicklung havejointly developed the world's first Japanese-to-German translation softwaresystem.andP;  The new prototype system is based on Fujitsu's Atlas-II softwarewhich is now used for translating Japanese into English.andP;  Aris programmed a50,000-word German dictionary, some 12,000 rules of grammar, and developmenttools in this version of the Atlas software.andP;  The software will run onFujitsu's S Family and Sun Microsystems' Sun-3 and Sun-4 workstations.andO;Running on the Sun 4/110 workstation with RISC-type (reduced instruction setcomputer) SPARC chips, the new software system translates about 6,000Japanese words to German per hour.andP;  The software is still in the testingstage; Fujitsu hopes to begin selling the software next year.andP;  (KenTakahashi/19890817)</TEXT></DOC>